                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d525">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.0144/95</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fletcher</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-08T19:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 8, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1047. Commanding Officer, Southern Department, telegraphed May 1 as follows:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Commanding officer Big Bend district reports that one of his patrols of
                            10 men was attacked this morning at 4 o’clock by a force of between 25
                            and 50 Mexicans who were on the American side of the Rio Grande near
                            Neville ranch. No casualties.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Bring substance foregoing earnestly to attention Mexican Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
